B

• [Ballast](/Ballast) – This is material strategically employed to provide stability to vehicles or structures. In maritime contexts, ballast might be added to ships to improve [stability](/Ship_stability). In aeronautics, gondolas of [balloons](/Balloon_(aircraft)) and [airships](/Airship) use ballast. It’s simply a means of adding weight for equilibrium.

• [Barrier cable](/Barrier_cable) – A type of restraint system designed for vehicles or pedestrians. It typically consists of a steel strand, similar in construction to those used in [post-tensioned concrete](/Post-tensioned_concrete). It’s a safety measure, a physical deterrent.

• [Beam](/Beam_(structure)) – A fundamental [structural element](/Structural_element), a beam's primary role is to resist loads applied laterally to its axis. Its characteristic mode of deformation is [bending](/Bending). The applied loads induce reaction forces at the supports and internal [shear forces](/Shear_force) and [bending moments](/Bending_moment), which in turn create stresses, strains, and deflections. Beams are classified by their support conditions, cross-sectional shape, length, and material.

• [Bearing capacity](/Bearing_capacity) – This refers to the ability of [soil](/Soil) to withstand applied [loads](/Structural_load). It’s the maximum average contact [pressure](/Pressure) a [foundation](/Foundation_(architecture)) can exert on the soil without causing [shear](/Shear_strength_(soil)) failure. The ultimate bearing capacity is the theoretical maximum, while the allowable bearing capacity incorporates a [factor of safety](/Factor_of_safety). In softer soils, settlement can be the limiting factor, even without shear failure. The three primary failure modes are general shear, local shear, and punching shear.

• [Bending](/Bending) – In the field of [applied mechanics](/Applied_mechanics), bending, or flexure, describes the behavior of a slender [structural](/Structural) element when subjected to an external [load](/Structural_load) applied perpendicular to its longitudinal axis. It’s the fundamental way beams deform under load.

• [Bending moment](/Bending_moment) – This is the internal reaction within a [structural element](/Structural_element) caused by an external [force](/Force) or [moment](/Moment_of_force) that induces [bending](/Bending). It’s a critical factor in structural analysis, directly influencing stresses and potential failure.

• [Benefit–cost analysis](/Benefit%E2%80%93cost_analysis) – Often abbreviated as CBA, this is a systematic method for evaluating the strengths and weaknesses of different alternatives. The goal is to identify the option that yields the greatest benefits while minimizing costs. It's commonly applied to business transactions, policy decisions, and investment projects, providing a quantitative framework for decision-making.

• [Bent (structural)](/Bent_(structural)) – Bents are the fundamental building blocks that define the overall form and character of a structure. Unlike a specific [Pratt truss](/Truss_bridge), a bent is a cross-sectional template of structural members – like rafters, joists, and posts – that repeats along the length of the structure. Bents aren't limited to a single material; they can be constructed from timber, steel, or even concrete. They are the repeating structural ribs that give a building its skeleton.

• [Bistable structure](/Bistable_structure) – A structure possessing two distinct stable equilibrium states.

• [Brick](/Brick) – A ubiquitous building material, bricks are used to construct walls, pavements, and other elements in [masonry](/Masonry) construction. Traditionally made of [clay](/Clay), bricks are now also manufactured from clay-bearing soil, sand, and [lime](/Lime_(material)), or from [concrete](/Concrete). They are typically joined with [mortar](/Mortar_(masonry)), adhesives, or through interlocking designs. Bricks come in a vast array of classes, types, materials, and sizes, varying by region and historical period. They are broadly categorized as fired or non-fired.

• [Brickwork](/Brickwork) – This is the art and practice of [masonry](/Masonry) created by a [bricklayer](/Bricklayer) using [bricks](/Brick) and [mortar](/Mortar_(masonry)). Rows of bricks, known as [courses](/Course_(architecture)), are laid sequentially to build up structures like brick [walls](/Wall).

• [Bridge](/Bridge) – A structure engineered to span a physical obstacle, such as a [body of water](/Body_of_water), [valley](/Valley), or [road](/Road), allowing passage over it without impeding the flow beneath.

• [Brittle](/Brittle) – Describing a material that fractures with little or no deformation when subjected to stress.

• [Buckling-restrained braced frame](/Buckling-restrained_braced_frame) – A type of seismic force-resisting system designed to prevent buckling in its braces.

• [Building engineering](/Building_engineering) – A discipline focused on the structural integrity, systems, and construction of buildings.

• [Building services engineering](/Building_services_engineering) – This field deals with the design, installation, and maintenance of a building's essential systems, including heating, ventilation, air conditioning (HVAC), plumbing, and electrical systems.

• [Bulk modulus](/Bulk_modulus) – A measure of a substance's resistance to uniform compression.

