C

• [Calcium aluminate cements](/Calcium_aluminate_cements) – These are [cements](/Cement) primarily composed of hydraulic calcium aluminates. Also known as aluminous cement, high-alumina cement, or "Ciment fondu" in French, they find use in specialized, smaller-scale applications.

• [Camber beam](/Camber_beam) – In construction, a camber beam is a piece of [timber](/Timber) or steel that is deliberately shaped with an upward curve in the middle. This slight arch, ideally parabolic but often a circular segment, is used in platforms and other structures where long, strong [beams](/Beam_(structure)) are required, providing a subtle upward force to counteract expected downward deflection.

• [Castellated beam](/Castellated_beam) – This is a type of [beam](/Beam_(structure)) fabrication technique. An [I-beam](/I-beam) is cut longitudinally along its web in a specific pattern, then reassembled to create a deeper web, leveraging the geometry of the cuts. It's a way to gain strength and depth efficiently.

• [Cant](/Cant_(road/rail)) – Also known as superelevation or banking, cant is the transverse slope of a [railway](/Railway) track or road. It's particularly pronounced on curves, where the outer rail or edge is raised to allow vehicles to navigate the turn more safely and at higher speeds than would be possible on a flat surface.

• [Cantilever](/Cantilever) – A rigid [structural element](/Structural_element), like a [beam](/Beam_(structure)) or plate, that is fixed at one end and extends outwards, unsupported at the other. It's a classic example of a structure resisting loads through bending.

• [Cantlop Bridge](/Cantlop_Bridge) – A specific, historical bridge structure.

• [Carbon steel](/Carbon_steel) – An [alloy](/Alloy) of iron and carbon, characterized by its strength and hardness.

• [Cast iron](/Cast_iron) – An [alloy](/Alloy) of [iron](/Iron) and [carbon](/Carbon) with a carbon content exceeding 2%. Its utility stems from its relatively low melting point, making it easier to cast into complex shapes.

• [Casting](/Casting) – A manufacturing process where a liquid material is poured into a mold and allowed to solidify.

• [Catenary](/Catenary) – The curve formed by a flexible chain or cable hanging freely between two points under its own weight.

• [Cavity wall](/Cavity_wall) – A wall constructed with an internal void between the inner and outer layers, improving thermal insulation and moisture resistance.

• [Cement](/Cement) – A binder substance used in construction that sets, hardens, and adheres to other materials to bind them together.

• [Cement render](/Cement_render) – A coating applied to walls, typically composed of cement, sand, and water, used for protection and decoration.

• [Collar beam](/Collar_beam) – A horizontal timber connecting two opposing rafters in a roof structure, typically located higher up than a tie beam.

• [Color-tagged structure](/Color-tagged_structure) – A structure where components are marked with specific colors to indicate their properties or assembly sequence.

• [Column](/Column) – A vertical structural element designed to carry and transmit compressive loads from a [superstructure](/Bridge) to a [foundation](/Foundation_(architecture)).

• [Common rafter](/Rafter) – A principal sloped structural member of a roof.

• [Composite order](/Composite_order) – A classical [architectural order](/Classical_architecture) that combines elements of the Ionic and Corinthian orders.

• [Compressive strength](/Compressive_strength) – The ability of a material or structure to withstand an applied compressive load without failure.

• [Computer-aided design](/Computer-aided_design) – The use of computer systems to assist in the creation, modification, analysis, or optimization of a design.

• [Computer-aided engineering](/Computer-aided_engineering) – The use of computer software to simulate performance in order to improve product designs or assist in the resolution of engineering problems.

• [Concrete](/Concrete) – A composite material composed of fine and coarse [aggregate](/Construction_aggregate) bonded together with a fluid cement ([cement](/Cement)) that hardens over time, typically [hydraulic cement](/Cement).

• [Concrete masonry unit](/Concrete_masonry_unit) – Precast concrete blocks used in masonry construction.

• [Concrete pump](/Concrete_pump) – A machine used for transferring liquid concrete by pumping.

• [Construction aggregate](/Construction_aggregate) – See [Aggregate (construction)](/Construction_aggregate).

• [Construction engineering](/Construction_engineering) – A specialized field within [civil engineering](/Civil_engineering) focused on the planning, management, and execution of construction projects.

• [Construction surveying](/Construction_surveying) – The surveying activities required to lay out structures and facilities on the ground.

• [Corbel](/Corbel) – A structural piece of stone, wood, or metal jutting from a wall to carry a superincumbent weight.

• [Corinthian order](/Corinthian_order) – The most ornate of the classical [Greek architectural orders](/Classical_architecture), characterized by a capital decorated with acanthus leaves.

• [Corrosion](/Corrosion) – The gradual destruction of materials by chemical and/or electrochemical reaction with their environment.

• [Corrosion fatigue](/Corrosion_fatigue) – Failure of a material under cyclic loading in a corrosive environment.

• [Corrugated galvanised iron](/Corrugated_galvanised_iron) – Sheet metal with a specific profile, coated with zinc for corrosion protection, often used for roofing and cladding.

• [Crane](/Crane_(machine)) – A machine for lifting and moving heavy objects.

• [Cross brace](/Cross_brace) – A diagonal member used to stiffen a structure.

• [Cross bracing](/Cross_bracing) – A system of diagonal members forming an 'X' or 'V' shape, used to provide rigidity.

• [Curvilinear motion](/Curvilinear_motion) – Motion along a curved path.

