H

• [H-beam](/I-beam) – A structural steel section with an H-shaped cross-section, often used as beams or columns. Also known as a wide-flange beam.

• [Half-timbering](/Timber_framing) – A type of [timber framing](/Timber_framing) where the structural timbers are visible on the exterior of a building.

• [Hammerbeam roof](/Hammerbeam_roof) – A type of roof structure featuring projecting hammerbeams that support the main principals.

• [Hardness](/Hardness) – A measure of a material's resistance to scratching, indentation, or abrasion.

• [Hardwood](/Hardwood) – Wood from deciduous trees, generally denser and stronger than softwood.

• [Header](/Framing_(construction)) – A structural member placed perpendicular to joists or rafters, often framing an opening.

• [Henderson–Hasselbalch equation](/Henderson%E2%80%93Hasselbalch_equation) – An equation used in chemistry to calculate the pH of a buffer solution.

• High strength bolt – A bolt designed for use in structural connections, capable of withstanding high tensile and shear loads.

• [High-tensile steel](/Carbon_steel) – Steel with a high yield strength, often used in structural applications where reduced material is desired.

• [Hip roof](/Hip_roof) – A roof with slopes on all four sides, meeting at the ridge and hips.

• [Hod](/Brick_hod) – A triangular carrier used by bricklayers to transport bricks and mortar.

• [Hoist](/Hoist_(device)) – A device used for lifting or lowering loads.

• [Hollow structural section](/Hollow_structural_section) – Structural steel members with a hollow, typically square or rectangular, cross-section.

• [Honeycomb structure](/Honeycomb_structure) – A structure that resembles a honeycomb, offering high strength-to-weight ratio.

• [Hydraulic cement](/Cement) – [Cement](/Cement) that sets and hardens by chemical reaction with water.

• [Hydraulic engineering](/Hydraulic_engineering) – The application of engineering principles to the control and use of water.

