I

• [I-beam](/I-beam) – A structural steel section with an I-shaped cross-section, commonly used as beams. Also known as a rolled steel joist or universal beam.

• [Imposed load](/Structural_load) – Loads on a structure that are not permanent, such as those from people, furniture, or snow. Also known as live load.

• [Infill wall](/Infill_wall) – Non-load-bearing walls used to enclose spaces within a structural frame.

• [Inflatable space structures](/Inflatable_space_structures) – Structures designed to be deployed in space by inflating them.

• [Influence line](/Influence_line) – A graphical representation used in [structural analysis](/Structural_analysis) to show the variation of a reaction or internal force along a structure as a unit load moves across it.

• [Insulating concrete form](/Insulating_concrete_form) – Permanent or removable forms used to create insulated concrete walls.

• [International Structural Engineering and Construction Society](/International_Structural_Engineering_and_Construction_Society) – A professional organization for structural engineers.

• [International System of Units](/International_System_of_Units) – The modern form of the metric system, used globally in science and engineering.

• [Interval estimation](/Interval_estimation) – A range of values, derived from statistical data, that is likely to contain an unknown population parameter.

• [Intrados](/Arch) – The inner curve or surface of an arch.

• [Iron](/Iron) – A chemical element, a strong, magnetic, silvery-white metal, widely used in [structural steel](/Structural_steel).

J

• [Jack rafter](/Rafter) – A rafter that forms part of a hip or valley in a roof.

• [Jackscrew](/Jackscrew) – A mechanical device that lifts heavy weights by turning a threaded screw.

• [Jetty](/Jetty) – A structure built out into a body of water to influence the current or tide, or to protect a harbor.

• [Joinery](/Woodworking_joints) – The craft of connecting pieces of wood, especially in furniture or buildings.

• [Jointing](/Brickwork) – The process of filling the gaps between bricks with mortar.

• [Joist](/Joist) – A horizontal structural member used in framing to support a floor or ceiling.

K

• [Kee Klamp](/Kee_Klamp) – A proprietary system of fittings used to create structures from tubing.

• [Kentledge](/Kentledge) – Heavy material, such as iron pigs, used as ballast.

• [Keystone](/Keystone_(architecture)) – The wedge-shaped stone at the apex of a masonry arch, locking the other stones in place.

• [King post](/King_post) – A vertical tension member in a [king post truss](/King_post).

• [King post truss](/King_post) – A type of [truss](/Truss) used in roofs and bridges, characterized by a central vertical king post.

L

• [Lally column](/Lally_column) – A round, thin-walled [structural steel](/Structural_steel) [column](/Column) filled with [concrete](/Concrete), used to support beams or timbers over long [spans](/Span_(architecture)). It's a common, robust support element.

• [Lightening holes](/Lightening_holes) – Openings in structural members to reduce weight without significantly compromising strength.

• [Limit load (physics)](/Limit_load_(physics)) – The maximum load a structure can sustain before undergoing significant deformation or failure.

• [Limit state design](/Limit_state_design) – A design philosophy that considers the various limit states (e.g., ultimate strength, serviceability) that a structure may reach.

• [Linear elasticity](/Linear_elasticity) – A material behavior where stress is directly proportional to strain, and the material returns to its original shape upon unloading.

• [Lintel](/Framing_(construction)) – A horizontal structural element spanning an opening, such as a doorway or window.

• [Live load](/Structural_load) – See [Imposed load](/Imposed_load).

• Load bearing – The ability of a structural element to support applied loads.

• [Load-bearing wall](/Load-bearing_wall) – A wall designed to carry structural loads from floors, roofs, or other walls above.

